        <div class="section">
            <h2>About Jainism</h2>
            <p>Jainism is an ancient Indian religion that emphasizes non-violence (ahimsa), self-discipline, and the pursuit of liberation from the cycle of birth and death (samsara). It was founded by Lord Mahavira, a contemporary of Buddha.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Fundamental Principles</h2>
            <p>Jainism is based on three core principles: Ahimsa (non-violence), Anekantavada (non-absolutism or multiple perspectives), and Aparigraha (non-possessiveness). Practitioners aim to avoid causing harm to all living beings and follow a path of right conduct.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Path to Liberation</h2>
            <p>The path to liberation in Jainism involves practicing self-discipline, leading a simple life, and cultivating detachment from material possessions and desires. Jain monks and nuns follow a strict ascetic lifestyle in pursuit of spiritual liberation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Beliefs and Practices</h2>
            <p>Jainism recognizes the existence of eternal souls in all living beings, and the ultimate goal is to achieve moksha (liberation) by purifying the soul from karmas through right knowledge, right faith, and right conduct.</p>
